The article highlights President Obama's belief that major economies have a responsibility to combat corruption and establish frameworks to ensure market integrity. The United States has been a leader in this effort, passing the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act and creating the Anti-Bribery Convention and the United Nations Convention against Corruption. The article also mentions the establishment of the Financial Action Task Force and the G-8's role in advancing the anti-corruption agenda. The G-20 has reaffirmed its commitment to combating corruption and announced the establishment of a high-level experts group to develop concrete commitments in key areas such as anti-bribery rules, fighting corruption in the public and private sectors, and preventing corrupt officials from accessing the global financial system. The United States sees corruption as a core part of the G-20's mandate and believes that tackling corruption is crucial for shaping a rules-based and transparent international economic architecture.